        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#oliverio1930"/>, p. 222, n. <citedRange>39</citedRange> (ph.)</bibl>, whence
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.306</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#cdl1970"/>, p. 240, n. <citedRange>7</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>000900</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><name><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name>
                    <persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65836"><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Τιμῶχος"><unclear>Τ</unclear>ιμό̄χō</name></persName> 
                    <g type="punct">:</g> <persName type="divine" ref="#Apollo"><name nymRef="#Ἀπόλλων">τὀ<supplied reason="lost">πόλōνι</supplied></name></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Un tel, fils</supplied> de Timokhos à <supplied reason="lost">Apollon</supplied>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">So-and-so, son</supplied> of Timochos for <supplied reason="lost">Apollo</supplied>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Il tale, figlio</supplied> di Timochos ad <supplied reason="lost">Apollo</supplied>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>For the name <foreign xml:lang="grc">Τίμουχος</foreign>, see <bibl><ptr target="#cdl1988"/></bibl>.</p>
	<p>As complete denominations with name and father's name are very rare in such graffiti of dedication, we might also imagine another formulation:
	    instead of a lost personal name followed by Timochos as a father's name, the word <foreign xml:lang="grc">δεκάτα</foreign> might have been lost 
	    and the reading would then be '(tithe) of Timouchos for Apollo'.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
